{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17496639","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17496639"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T08:52:22+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T08:52:22+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1399"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1399","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1399"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.13,0.15,0.63,0.04,0.06]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1399"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115921"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1399","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1399"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1399"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97917"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"2"},{"type":"tags","id":"11"},{"type":"tags","id":"13"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"160"},{"type":"tags","id":"1114"},{"type":"tags","id":"2074"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4982"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"13110"},{"type":"contributions","id":"31209"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42304"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43077"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44268"},{"type":"contributions","id":"49256"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115921","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/115921"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 45-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with a 12-hour history of sharp right-sided chest pain and sudden onset shortness of breath. The pain worsens with deep inspiration and does not radiate. She returned to Australia two days ago after a 24-hour flight home from Europe with limited mobility during the journey. She has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications. She does not smoke and drinks alcohol occasionally. There is no history of recent surgery, trauma, hormone therapy, or malignancy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well. Her pulse rate is 88/min, blood pressure 128/66 mmHg, respiratory rate 20/min, SpO2 96% on room air, and temperature 37.2\u00b0C. Cardiovascular and respiratory examinations are unremarkable with no signs of right heart strain. A D-dimer is elevated at 1.2 mg/L (\u0026lt;0.5). A CT pulmonary angiogram shows a small segmental pulmonary embolism without evidence of right ventricular strain.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate course of treatment?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Thrombolysis with alteplase","Enoxaparin for one month","Apixaban for three months","Indefinite low dose apixaban","Dabigatran for six months"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EPulmonary embolism is managed according to the patient\u0027s haemodynamic status, the clot burden, and the presence of provoking factors that influence the risk of recurrence. In haemodynamically stable patients, anticoagulation is the mainstay of treatment. Duration is tailored to whether the event is provoked by a transient risk factor, unprovoked, or associated with ongoing risks such as active cancer.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EApixaban for three months\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate option. This patient is stable, has a small segmental pulmonary embolism, and a clear transient provoking non-surgical risk factor (prolonged travel with immobility). Hence, three to six months of anticoagulation is appropriate in this setting. A direct oral anticoagulant (DOAC), such as apixaban or rivaroxaban, is preferred for the treatment of venous thromboembolism (VTE) in the absence of contraindications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThrombolysis with alteplase\u003C/strong\u003E is reserved for massive pulmonary embolism with haemodynamic instability or shock. This patient is stable, with normal blood pressure and no signs of right heart strain, so thrombolysis is not indicated.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEnoxaparin for one month\u003C/strong\u003E is inadequate in duration. DOACs are the preferred anticoagulants in VTE unless there are contraindications, such as unoperated gastrointestinal cancer.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIndefinite low-dose apixaban\u003C/strong\u003E is an option for extended secondary prevention after the initial full-treatment phase in selected higher-risk patients. It is not appropriate as initial therapy, and indefinite treatment is generally not indicated for a clearly transiently provoked event.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDabigatran for six months\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect. While dabigatran is effective for the treatment of VTE, it requires initial parenteral therapy, and it is not listed on the PBS for this indication.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["A pulmonary embolism provoked by a transient non-surgical risk factor (e.g, recent long-haul travel) is treated with three to six months of anticoagulation.","Direct oral anticoagulants are preferred first-line agents for most people with pulmonary embolism who are haemodynamically stable."],"references":["Doherty S. Pulmonary embolism: An update. Australian Family Physician. 2017;46:816-20.","Stevens H, Tran H, Gibbs H. Venous thromboembolism: current management. Aust Prescr 2019;42:123-6","Tran HA, Gibbs H, Merriman E, Curnow JL, Young L, Bennett A, Tan CW, Chunilal SD, Ward CM, Baker R, Nandurkar H. New guidelines from the Thrombosis and Haemostasis Society of Australia and New Zealand for the diagnosis and management of venous thromboembolism. Med J Aust. 2019 Mar;210(5):227-235. Available from: https://www.mja.com.au/journal/2019/210/5/new-guidelines-thrombosis-and-haemostasis-society-australia-and-new-zealand"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97917"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1399"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97917","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/97917"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-26T12:27:18+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-26T12:29:24+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1399"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115921"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"2","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/2"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec0","name":"Cardiology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:21+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"11","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec1","name":"Respiratory Medicine","synonyms":["Pulmonology"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"13","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/13"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\ude78","name":"Haematology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,